The '''cutthroat trout''' {{nowrap|(''Oncorhynchus clarki'')}} is a fish species of the [[salmonidae]] [[Family (biology)|family]] native to cold-water [[tributary|tributaries]] of the Pacific Ocean, [[Rocky Mountains]] and [[Great Basin]] in North America. As a member of the genus ''[[Oncorhynchus]]'', it is one of the Pacific [[trout]], a group that includes the widely distributed [[rainbow trout]]. Cutthroat trout are popular [[gamefish]], especially among [[Angling|angler]]s who enjoy [[fly fishing]]. The common name "cutthroat" refers to the distinctive red coloration on the underside of the [[Mandible|lower jaw]]. The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] ''clarki'' was given to honor explorer [[William Clark (explorer)|William Clark]], coleader of the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]].

Cutthroat trout usually inhabit and [[Spawn (biology)|spawn]] in small to moderately large, clear, well-[[Oxygenation (environmental)|oxygenated]], shallow rivers with gravel bottoms. They also reproduce in clear, cold, moderately deep lakes. They are native to the [[Alluvium|alluvial]] or [[freestone stream]]s that are typical tributaries of the Pacific basin, Great Basin and Rocky Mountains. Cutthroat trout spawn in the spring and may inadvertently but naturally [[hybrid (biology)|hybridize]] with rainbow trout, producing fertile [[cutbow]]s. Some [[population]]s of the coastal cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. clarki'')}} are [[anadromous|semi-anadromous]].

Several [[subspecies]] of cutthroat trout are currently listed as [[threatened species|threatened]] in their native ranges due to [[habitat loss]] and the [[introduced species|introduction]] of non-native species. Two subspecies, {{nowrap|''O. c. alvordensis''}} and {{nowrap|''O. c. macdonaldi''}}, are considered [[extinct]]. Cutthroat trout are raised in [[fish hatchery|hatcheries]] to restore populations in their native range, as well as stock non-native lake environments to support angling. The cutthroat trout type species and several subspecies are the [[List of U.S. state fish|official state fish]] of seven western U.S. states.

==Taxonomy==
[[File:Phylogenetic Map of Oncorhynchus clarki.jpg|thumb|alt=Drawing of Phylogenetic evolution map for cutthroat trout|[[Phylogenetics|Phylogenetic map]] of {{nowrap|''Oncorhynchus clarki''}}<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-138>{{cite book|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J.|authorlink=Robert J. Behnke |author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|title=Trout and Salmon of North America |publisher=The Free Press|isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|pages=138<U+2013>139|chapter=Cutthroat trout ''Oncorhynchus clarki''}}</ref>]]
The scientific name of the cutthroat trout is {{nowrap|''Oncorhynchus clarki''}}. Cutthroat trout were the first [[New World]] trout encountered by Europeans when in 1541, Spanish explorer [[Francisco de Coronado]] recorded seeing trout in the [[Pecos River]] near [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]. These were most likely Rio Grande cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. virginalis'')}}<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-139>{{cite book|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J.|authorlink=Robert J. Behnke |author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|title=Trout and Salmon of North America |publisher=The Free Press|isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|page=139|chapter=Cutthroat trout ''Oncorhynchus clarki''}}</ref> The species was first described in the journals of explorer William Clark from specimens obtained during the Lewis and Clark Expedition from the [[Missouri River]] near [[Great Falls, Montana]], and these were most likely the [[westslope cutthroat trout]] {{nowrap|(''O. c. lewisi'')}}. As one of Lewis and Clark's many missions was to describe the flora and fauna encountered during their expedition, cutthroat trout were given the name {{nowrap|''Salmo clarki''}} in honor of William Clark.<ref name=richardson/> In 1836, the [[type specimen]] of {{nowrap|''S. clarki''}} was described by naturalist [[John Richardson (naturalist)|John Richardson]] from a tributary of the lower [[Columbia River]], identified as the "Katpootl",<ref name=richardson/> which was perhaps the [[Lewis River (Washington)|Lewis River]] as there was a [[Multnomah (tribe)|Multnomah]] village of similar name at the [[confluence]]. This type specimen was most likely the coastal cutthroat trout subspecies {{nowrap|''O. c. clarki''}}.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-146>{{cite book|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J.|authorlink=Robert J. Behnke|author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|title=Trout and Salmon of North America|publisher=The Free Press|isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|page=146|chapter=Cutthroat trout ''Oncorhynchus clarki''}}</ref> Until the 1960s, populations of westslope cutthroat trout and Yellowstone cutthroat trout were lumped into one subspecies; ''Salmo clarki lewisi''. Biologists later split the group into two subspecies, christening the name Westslope cutthroat trout with the ''lewisi'' name which honors explorer [[Meriwether Lewis]] and renaming the Yellowstone cutthroat trout ''Salmo bouvieri'',<ref>{{cite book|title=About Trout: The Best of Robert J. Behnke from ''Trout Magazine''|page=12|publisher=Globe Pequot|authorlink=Robert J. Behnke|year=2007|isbn=978-1-59921-203-6|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J.|author2=Williams, Ted}}</ref> the first name given to the Yellowstone cutthroat trout by [[David Starr Jordan]] in 1883 honoring a U.S. Army Captain Bouvier.<ref>{{cite book|last=Trotter|first=Patrick C.|title=Cutthroat: Native Trout of the West |publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, CA|year=2008|edition=2nd|isbn=978-0-520-25458-9|chapter=Yellowstone Cutthroat Trout|page=258}}</ref>

In 1989, [[Morphology (biology)|morphological]] and [[Genetics|genetic]] studies indicated trout of the [[Pacific ocean|Pacific basin]] were genetically closer to Pacific salmon (''Oncorhynchus'' species) than to the ''[[Salmo]]s''<U+2013>[[brown trout]] {{nowrap|(''S. trutta'')}} or [[Atlantic salmon]] {{nowrap|(''S. salar'')}} of the [[Atlantic ocean|Atlantic basin]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Classification and Scientific Names of Rainbow and Cutthroat Trouts|journal=Fisheries|author4=Gerald R. Smith, Ralph F. Stearley|volume=14|number=1 |year=1989|publisher=American Fisheries Society|pages=4<U+2013>10|doi=10.1577/1548-8446(1989)014<0004:TCASNO>2.0.CO;2|last1=Smith|first1=Gerald R.|last2=Stearley|first2=Ralph F.}}</ref> Thus, in 1989, taxonomic authorities moved the rainbow, cutthroat and other Pacific basin trout into the genus ''Oncorhynchus''.<ref name=BehnkeO.>{{cite book|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J. |authorlink=Robert J. Behnke|author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|title=Trout and Salmon of North America|publisher=The Free Press |isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|pages=10<U+2013>21|chapter=Genus ''Oncorhynchus''}}</ref>

===Subspecies===
The 14 recognized [[subspecies]] of cutthroat trout are each native to a separate geographic area. Scientists believe the cutthroat trout evolved from a common ''Oncorhynchus'' ancestor that migrated along the Pacific coast and into the mountain west primarily via the Columbia and [[Snake River|Snake]] river basins 3-5&nbsp;million years ago, in the late [[Pliocene]] or early [[Pleistocene]] epochs. These epochs had repeated [[glacial period|glacial]] and [[interglacial]] periods that would have caused repeated fracturing and isolation of cutthroat trout populations, eventually resulting in the different subspecies found today.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki>{{cite book|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J.|authorlink=Robert J. Behnke|author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|title=Trout and Salmon of North America|publisher=The Free Press|isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|pages=137<U+2013>234|chapter=Cutthroat trout ''Oncorhynchus clarki''}}</ref> The 14 subspecies are found in four evolutionary groups<U+2014>Coastal, Westslope, Yellowstone and Lahontan.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-138/>

