==Description==
[[File:Yellowstone cutthroat trout slash.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Photo of cutthroat trout head with red throat slashes|Head of Yellowstone cutthroat trout {{nowrap|''O. c. bouvieri''}}, showing characteristic red throat slashes]]
Throughout their native and introduced ranges, cutthroat trout vary widely in size, coloration and habitat selection. Their coloration can range from golden to gray to green on the back. Cutthroat trout can generally be distinguished from rainbow trout by the presence of [[Branchial arch|basibranchial teeth]] at the base of tongue and a [[maxilla]]ry that extends beyond the posterior edge of the eye.<ref>{{cite book|last=Trotter|first=Patrick C.|title=Cutthroat: Native Trout of the West|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, CA |year=2008|edition=2nd|isbn=978-0-520-25458-9|page=16}}</ref> Depending on subspecies, [[Strain (biology)|strain]] and habitat, most have distinctive red, pink, or orange linear marks along the underside of their [[mandible]]s in the lower folds of the [[gill]] plates. These markings are responsible for the common name "cutthroat", first given to the trout by outdoor writer [[Charles Hallock]] in an 1884 article in ''The American Angler''.<ref name=Trotter>{{cite book |last=Trotter|first=Patrick C.|title=Cutthroat: Native Trout of the West|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, CA|year=2008|edition=2nd|isbn=978-0-520-25458-9|page=13}}</ref> These markings are not unique to the species, some coastal rainbow trout {{nowrap|(''Oncorhynchus mykiss irideus'')}} and [[Columbia River redband trout]] {{nowrap|(''O. m. gairdneri'')}} populations also display reddish or pink throat markings.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki/>

At maturity, different populations and subspecies of cutthroat trout can range from {{convert|6|to|40|in|cm}} in length, depending on habitat and food availability. Sea-run forms of coastal cutthroat trout average {{convert|2|to|5|lbs|kg|1}}. The length and weights of mature inland forms vary widely depending on their particular environment and availability of food. Stream-resident fish are much smaller, {{convert|0.4|to|3.2|oz|g}}, while [[lake|lacustrine]] populations have attained weights ranging from {{convert|12|to|17|lbs|kg|abbr=on}} in ideal conditions.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki/> The largest cutthroat trout subspecies is the Lahontan cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. henshawi'')}}. These fish average {{convert|8|to|9|in|cm|abbr=on}} in small streams and {{convert|8|to|22|in|cm|abbr=on}} in larger rivers and lakes. In ideal environments, the Lahontan cutthroat trout attains typical weights of {{convert|0.25|to|8|lbs|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki/> The world record cutthroat trout is a Lahontan at {{convert|39|in|cm|abbr=on}} and {{convert|41|lbs|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref name=IGFA/>

===Lifecycle===
Cutthroat trout usually inhabit and spawn in small to moderately large, clear, well-oxygenated, shallow rivers with [[gravel]] bottoms. They are native to the alluvial or [[freestone stream]]s typical of tributaries of the Pacific Basin, Great Basin and Rocky Mountains. They spawn in the spring, as early as February in coastal rivers and as late as July in high mountain lakes and streams. Spawning begins when water temperatures reach {{convert|43|to|46|F|abbr=on}}.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-141>{{cite book|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J.|authorlink=Robert J. Behnke |author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|title=Trout and Salmon of North America |publisher=The Free Press|isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|pages=141<U+2013>142|chapter=Cutthroat trout ''Oncorhynchus clarki''}}</ref> Cutthroat trout construct a [[Spawn (biology)#Brood hiders|redd]] in the stream gravel to lay eggs. The female selects the site for and excavates the redd. Females, depending on size, lay between 200 and 4,400&nbsp;eggs. Eggs are fertilized with milt (sperm) by an attending male. Eggs hatch into [[Juvenile fish#Juvenile salmon|alevins]] or sac fry in about a month and spend two weeks in the gravel while they absorb their yolk sack before emerging. After emergence, [[Fry (biology)|fry]] begin feeding on [[zooplankton]]. Juvenile cutthroat trout typically mature in three to five years.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/nrcs143_010039.pdf |title= Cutthroat Trout (''Oncorhynchus clarki'') |publisher= U.S. Department of Agriculture |date=January 2007 |accessdate=2014-03-17}}</ref> Lake-resident cutthroat trout are usually found in moderately deep, cool lakes with adequate shallows and vegetation for good food production. Lake populations generally require access to gravel-bottomed streams to be self-sustaining, but occasionally spawn on shallow gravel beds with good water circulation.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-141/>

Cutthroat trout naturally interbreed with the closely related rainbow trout, producing fertile [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrids]] commonly called "cutbows". This hybrid generally bears similar coloration and overall appearance to the cutthroat trout, usually retaining the characteristic orange-red slash. Cutbow hybrids often pose a taxonomic difficulty when trying to distinguish any given specimen as a rainbow or cutthroat trout.<ref name=Halverson>{{cite book |last=Halverson|first=Anders|title=An Entirely Synthetic Fish: How Rainbow Trout Beguiled America and Overran the World|chapter=A Single New Mongrel Species|publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven, CT|pages=145<U+2013>164|isbn=978-0-300-14087-3|year=2010}}</ref> In addition, cutthroat trout may hybridize with {{nowrap|''O. gilae''}} the [[Gila trout]] and {{nowrap|''O. apache''}} the [[Apache trout]] in regions where their ranges overlap.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fws.gov/southwest/es/arizona/Documents/SpeciesDocs/Apache_Trout/Apache%20Trout%20Recovery%20Plan%202nd%20Revision.pdf |title=Apache Trout ''Oncorhynchus apache'' Recovery Plan |publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service|date=August 2009|format=pdf|accessdate=2013-12-25}}</ref>

==Ecology==

===Range===
[[File:Oncorhynchus clarki range map.JPG|thumb|alt=Map of native and non-native range of cutthroat trout|Native and non-native U.S. range for ''O. clarki'', cutthroat trout<ref name=usgs>{{cite web|url=http://nas.er.usgs.gov/queries/factsheet.aspx?SpeciesID=890|title=NAS - Nonindigenous Aquatic Species-Oncorhynchus clarki|publisher=U.S. Geological Survey|accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref>]]
Cutthroat trout are native to western North America and have evolved through [[geographic isolation]] into 14 subspecies, each native to a different major [[drainage basin]]. Native cutthroat trout species are found along the [[Pacific Northwest]] coast from [[Alaska]] through British Columbia into northern [[California]], in the [[Cascade Range]], the [[Great Basin]] and throughout the Rocky Mountains including southern [[Alberta]].<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-145>{{cite book|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J.|authorlink=Robert J. Behnke|author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|title=Trout and Salmon of North America|publisher=The Free Press|isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|pages=143<U+2013>145|chapter=Cutthroat trout ''Oncorhynchus clarki''}}</ref> Some coastal populations of the coastal cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. clarki'')}} are semianadromous, spending a few months in marine environments to feed as adults and returning to fresh water from fall through early spring to feed on insects and spawn. Cutthroat trout have the second-largest historic native range of North American trout; the [[lake trout]] {{nowrap|(''Salvelinus namaycush'')}} having the largest.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-143>{{cite book|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J.|authorlink=Robert J. Behnke|author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|title=Trout and Salmon of North America|publisher=The Free Press|isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|page=143|chapter=Cutthroat trout ''Oncorhynchus clarki''}}</ref> Ranges of some subspecies, particularly the westslope cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. lewisi'')}} have been reduced to less than 10&nbsp;percent of their historic range due to habitat loss and introduction of non-native species.<ref name=Halverson/>

Although members of ''Oncorhynchus'', the Pacific trout, three subspecies<U+2014>the westslope {{nowrap|(''O. c. lewisi'')}}, the greenback {{nowrap|(''O. c. stomias'')}} and Yellowstone cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. bouvieri'')}}<U+2014>evolved populations east of the [[Continental Divide of the Americas|Continental Divide]] in the upper Missouri river basin, upper [[Arkansas River|Arkansas]] and [[Platte river]] basins and upper Yellowstone river basin, each which drain into the Atlantic basin via the Mississippi river. Scientists believe that the climatic and geologic conditions 3 to 5&nbsp;million years ago allowed cutthroat trout from the Snake river to migrate over the divide into the Yellowstone plateau via [[Two Ocean Pass]]. There is also evidence that Yellowstone Lake once drained south into the Snake River drainage.<ref>{{cite book|last=Trotter|first=Patrick C.|title=Cutthroat: Native Trout of the West|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, CA|year=2008|edition=2nd|isbn=978-0-520-25458-9|chapter=Evolution and Prehistoric Distribution|pages=56<U+2013>57}}</ref> Evidence suggests that the westslope cutthroat trout was able to establish populations east of the divide via [[Summit lake (Montana)|Summit Lake]] at [[Marias Pass]] which at one time connected the [[Flathead river]] drainage with the upper Missouri river drainage.<ref>{{cite book|last=Trotter |first=Patrick C.|title=Cutthroat: Native Trout of the West|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, CA |year=2008 |edition=2nd|isbn=978-0-520-25458-9|chapter=Evolution and Prehistoric Distribution |page=51}}</ref> Scientists speculate that there are several mountain passes associated with the headwaters of the [[Colorado River]] drainage and Arkansas/Platte River drainages that would have allowed migration of cutthroat trout east of the divide.<ref>{{cite book|last=Trotter|first=Patrick C.|title=Cutthroat: Native Trout of the West |publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, CA|year=2008|edition=2nd|isbn=978-0-520-25458-9|chapter=Greenback Cutthroat Trout |pages=389<U+2013>398}}</ref>

Cutthroat trout have been introduced into non-native waters outside their historic native range, but not to the extent of the rainbow trout {{nowrap|(''O. mykiss'')}}.<ref name=usgs/> Within the native range of the Yellowstone cutthroat trout, U.S. Fisheries Bureau and National Park Service authorities introduced Yellowstone cutthroat trout into many fishless lakes in Yellowstone National Park.<ref name=Kendall3-9>{{Cite book|last=Kendall|first=W. C.|title=The Fishes of the Yellowstone National Park|publisher=Department of Commerce, Bureau of Fisheries |location=Washington D.C.|pages=3<U+2013>9|year=1915|url=https://archive.org/download/fishesofyellowst00kendrich/fishesofyellowst00kendrich.pdf|format=pdf}}</ref> Cutthroat trout were introduced into [[Lake Michigan]] tributaries in the 1890s and sporadically in the early 20th century, but never established wild populations. A population of Yellowstone cutthroat trout purportedly has been established in [[Lake Huron]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Crawford|first=Stephan Scott |title=Salmonine Introductions to the Laurentian Great Lakes: An Historical Review and Evaluation of Ecological Effects|publisher=National Research Council of Canada|year=2001|isbn=0-660-17639-4|page=74}}</ref> Although cutthroat trout are not native to [[Arizona]], they are routinely introduced by the Arizona Game and Fish Department into high mountain lakes in the [[White Mountains (Arizona)|White Mountains]] in the northeastern region of that state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azgfd.gov/h_f/fish_cutthroat_trout.shtml|title=Cutthroat Trout|publisher=Arizona Game and Fish Department|accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref>

===Habitat===
[[File:East Fork Bitterroot River.jpg|thumb|alt=Photo of mountain stream-typical cutthroat trout habitat|Typical cutthroat trout habitat in the East Fork of the [[Bitterroot River]], [[Sula, Montana]]]]
Cutthroat trout require cold, clear, well-oxygenated, shallow rivers with gravel bottoms or cold, moderately deep lakes. Healthy stream-side vegetation that reduces [[siltation]] is typical of healthy cutthroat trout habitat and [[North American beaver|beaver]] ponds may provide refuge during periods of drought and over winter.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Complementation of Habitats for Bonneville Cutthroat Trout in Watersheds Influenced by Beavers, Livestock, and Drought|author4=Seth M. White and Frank J. Rahel|journal=Transactions of the American Fisheries Society|issue=137|pages=881<U+2013>894|year=2008|url=http://www.uwyo.edu/frahel/pdfs/white-2008-1.pdf|format=pdf|accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Role of stream ice on Fall and Winter Movements and Habitat Use by Bull Trout and Cutthroat Trout in Montana Headwater Streams |author4=Michael J. Jakober & Thomas E. McMahon|journal=Transactions of the American Fisheries Society |year=1998|url=http://www.montana.edu/mcmahon/Jakober%20winter%20ice.pdf|format=pdf|accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref> Most populations stay in fresh water throughout their lives and are known as nonmigratory, stream-resident or [[riverine]] populations.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki/> The coastal cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. clarki'')}} is the only cutthroat trout subspecies to [[Coevolution|coevolve]] through its entire range with the coastal rainbow trout (''O. m. irideus''). Portions of the westslope cutthroat trout's {{nowrap|(''O. c. lewisi'')}} range overlap with the Columbia river redband trout {{nowrap|(''O. m. gairdneri'')}}, but the majority of its native range is in headwater tributary streams above major waterfalls and other barriers to upstream migration.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-158>{{cite book|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J.|authorlink=Robert J. Behnke|author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|title=Trout and Salmon of North America|publisher=The Free Press|isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|pages=158<U+2013>160|chapter=Westslope cutthroat trout ''Oncorhynchus clarki lewisi''}}</ref> At least three subspecies are confined to [[endorheic basin|isolated basin]]s in the Great Basin and can tolerate [[saline water|saline]] or [[alkalinity|alkaline]] water.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lahontan Cutthroat Trout ''Oncorhynchus clarki henshawi''|publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service|url=http://www.fws.gov/ecos/ajax/docs/life_histories/E00Y.html|accessdate=2013-12-30}}</ref>

Cutthroat trout are [[List of feeding behaviours|opportunistic feeders]]. Stream-resident cutthroat trout primarily feed on [[larva]]l, [[pupa]]l and adult forms of aquatic insects (typically [[Caddisfly|caddisflies]], [[Plecoptera|stoneflies]], [[mayflies]] and aquatic [[fly|diptera]]ns), and adult forms of terrestrial insects (typically [[ant]]s, [[beetle]]s, [[grasshopper]]s and [[Cricket (insect)|cricket]]s) that fall into the water, fish eggs, small fish, along with crayfish, shrimp and other crustaceans. As they grow the proportion of fish consumed increases in most populations. In saltwater estuaries and along beaches, Coastal cutthroat trout feed on small fish such as [[sculpin]]s, [[sand lance]], [[Salmon|salmon fry]] and [[herring]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Johnson|first=Les|title=Fly-Fishing Coastal Cutthroat Trout: Flies, Techniques, Conservation |publisher=Frank Amato Publishers|location=Portland, OR|year=2004|isbn=978-1-57188-334-6 |chapter=Life History of the the Coastal Cutthroat |pages=21<U+2013>26}}</ref> They also consume [[shrimp]], small [[squid]] and [[krill]]. In fresh water they consume the same diet as stream resident trout&mdash;aquatic insects and crustaceans, amphibians, earthworms, small fish and fish eggs.<ref>{{cite web|title=BC Conservation Data Centre: Species Summary Oncorhynchus clarkii Cutthroat Trout|publisher=Ministry of Environment, Government of British Columbia|url=http://a100.gov.bc.ca/pub/eswp/speciesSummary.do?id=17659|accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref> Within the range of the [[bull trout]] {{nowrap|(''Salvelinus confluentus'')}} the cutthroat trout is a [[forage fish]] for the [[Piscivore|piscivorous]] bull trout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.fws.gov/Pubs1/bulltrout.pdf|title=Bull Trout Facts (Salvelinus confluentus)|publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service|format=pdf|accessdate=2013-12-30}}</ref>

===Artificial propagation===
[[File:OFFICIALS OF THE U.S. FISH AND WILDLIFE SERVICE RELEASE CUTTHROAT TROUT INTO PYRAMID LAKE FROM SUTCLIFFE'S LANDING ON... - NARA - 553655.jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=Photo of men stocking trout in a lake|Stocking cutthroat trout at Pyramid Lake, Nevada, in 1973]]
Various subspecies of cutthroat trout are raised in commercial, state and federal [[fish hatchery|hatcheries]] for introduction into suitable native and non-native riverine and lacustrine environments. In the early 20th century, several hatcheries were established in Yellowstone National Park by the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service|U.S. Bureau of Fisheries]]. These hatcheries not only produced stocks of the Yellowstone cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. bouvieri'')}} for the park, but also took advantage of the great spawning stock of cutthroat trout to supply eggs to hatcheries around the U.S. Between the years 1901 and 1953 a total of 818&nbsp;million trout eggs were exported from the park to hatcheries throughout the U.S.<ref name=Grand100>{{Cite journal|last=Franke|first=Mary Ann|date=Fall 1996|title=A Grand Experiment<U+2014>100 Years of Fisheries Management in Yellowstone: Part I|journal=Yellowstone Science|volume=4 |issue=4|pages=5|url=http://www.greateryellowstonescience.org/files/pdf/1-FRANKE.pdf|format=pdf|accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref> The Lahontan National Fish Hatchery operated by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service exists to restore populations of the Lahontan cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. henshawi'')}} in [[Pyramid Lake (Nevada)|Pyramid]], [[Walker Lake (Nevada)|Walker]], [[Fallen Leaf Lake (California)|Fallen Leaf]], [[June Lake (California)|June]], Marlette, and Gull Lakes and the [[Truckee River]] in California and Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fws.gov/lahontannfhc/lnfh.html|title=The Lahontan National Fish Hatchery|publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service|accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref> The hatchery produces about 300,000<U+2013>400,000 Lahontan cutthroat trout fry annually. The [[Jackson National Fish Hatchery]] produces around 400,000 Snake River fine-spotted cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. behnkei'')}} annually to support fisheries in Idaho and Wyoming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fws.gov/jackson/production.htm|title=Jackson Species and Production|publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service|accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref> The Leadville National Fish Hatchery produces 125,000<U+2013>200,000 Snake River fine-spotted, greenback cutthroat and rainbow trout annually to support fishing in the [[Fryingpan River|Fryingpan]] and Arkansas River drainages and other Colorado waters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fws.gov/leadville/production.htm|title=Leadville Species and & Production|publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service|accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref> The [[Bozeman National Fish Hatchery|Bozeman Fish Technology Center]], formerly a cutthroat trout fish hatchery in [[Bozeman, Montana]], plays a major role in the restoration of the greenback {{nowrap|(''O. c. stomias'')}} and westslope cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. lewisi'')}} subspecies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fws.gov/bozemanfishtech/index.html|title=Bozeman Fish Technology Center|accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref>

==Population threats==
{{see also|Salmonid susceptibility to whirling disease}}
[[File:Oncorhynchus clarkii bouvieri 1904.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Colored drawing of Yellowstone cutthroat trout from 1904 book|Yellowstone cutthroat trout from ''Birds and Nature'', 1904]]
The historic native range of cutthroat trout has been reduced by [[overfishing]], urbanization and habitat loss due to mining, livestock grazing and logging. Population densities have been reduced and in some cases populations have disappeared though competition with non-native [[brook trout|brook]], brown, lake and rainbow trout, [[kokanee salmon]], [[lake whitefish]] and [[Mysida|mysis shrimp]] which were introduced in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-147>{{cite book|last1=Behnke|first1=Robert J.|authorlink=Robert J. Behnke|author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|title=Trout and Salmon of North America|publisher=The Free Press|isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|pages=147<U+2013>148|chapter=Cutthroat trout ''Oncorhynchus clarki''}}</ref> Scientists believe the westslope cutthroat trout will eventually be extirpated from the large lakes in Western Montana due to the [[trophic cascade]]s resulting from lake trout and mysis shrimp introductions.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Long-term Effects of a Trophic Cascade in a Large Lake Ecosystem |author=Ellisa, Bonnie K.; Stanford, Jack A.; Goodman, Daniel; Stafford, Craig P.; Gustafson, Daniel L.; Beauchamp, David A.; Chess, Dale W.; Craft, James A.; Deleray, Mark A.; Hansen, Barry S.|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=108 |issue=3 |pages=1070 |date=December 9, 2010 |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/early/2011/01/03/1013006108.full.pdf |format=pdf |publisher=National Academy of Sciences |accessdate=2014-03-12 |bibcode=2011PNAS..108.1070E |doi=10.1073/pnas.1013006108|pmid=21199944}}</ref> The most serious current threats to several subspecies are [[Hybrid (biology)#Interspecific hybrids|interspecific breeding]] with introduced rainbow trout creating hybrid cutbows and intraspecific breeding with other introduced cutthroat trout subspecies. In the [[Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem]], the presence of lake trout {{nowrap|(''Salvelinus namaycush'')}} in [[Yellowstone Lake]] in Yellowstone National Park has caused a serious decline in {{nowrap|(''O. c. bouvieri'')}}.<ref name=YSLakeTrout>{{cite journal|authors=Koel, Todd M.; Bigelow, Patricia E.; Doepke, Philip D.; Ertel, Brian D.; Mahony, Daniel L.|journal=Yellowstone Science|volume=14 |number=2 |title=Conserving Yellowstone Cutthroat Trout for the Future of the GYE |publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/yell/planyourvisit/upload/YS14(2).pdf |format=pdf|year=Spring 2006|pages=20<U+2013>28|accessdate=2014-03-12}}</ref> Outbreaks of [[Myxobolus cerebralis|whirling disease]] in major spawning tributaries within the native ranges have also caused declines. Most subspecies of cutthroat trout are highly susceptible to whirling disease, although the Snake River fine-spotted cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. behnkei'')}} appears to be resistant to the parasite.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nickum|first=David|title=Whirling Disease in the United States|publisher=[[Trout Unlimited]] |url=http://whirlingdisease.montana.edu/pdfs/TU_Report_99.pdf|format=pdf|accessdate=2014-03-01|date=January 1999}}</ref>

===Interspecific and intraspecific breeding===

The most serious impact on the genetic purity of most cutthroat trout subspecies results from interspecific and intraspecific breeding resulting in hybrids that carry the [[gene]]s of both parents. In inland populations, the introduction of rainbow trout from hatchery stocks have resulted in cutbow hybrids that continue to diminish the genetic purity of many cutthroat trout subspecies. The introduction of hatchery-raised Yellowstone cutthroat trout into native ranges of other cutthroat trout subspecies, particularly the westslope cutthroat trout, has resulted in intraspecific breeding and diminished genetic purity of the westslope subspecies. As such, populations of genetically pure westslope cutthroat trout are very rare and localized in streams above barriers to upstream migrations by introduced species.<ref name=Halverson/> Fisheries biologist [[Robert J. Behnke]] attributes the extinction of the yellowfin cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. macdonaldi'')}} and Alvord cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. alvordensis'')}} subspecies to the introduction of non-native rainbow trout.<ref name=BehnkeOclarki-201>{{cite book|last1=Behnke |first1=Robert J.|title=Trout and Salmon of North America|author2=Tomelleri, Joseph R. (illustrator)|publisher=Free Press|location=New York|isbn=0-7432-2220-2|year=2002|pages=201<U+2013>206, 221<U+2013>224}}</ref>

===Decline of the Yellowstone subspecies===
[[File:AnglersYellowstone-Haynes1897.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Old photo of anglers with a lot of fish from Yellowstone Lake|Anglers at West Thumb, 1897, with a harvest of Yellowstone cutthroat trout]]
The population at the core of the Yellowstone cutthroat trout's native range, in Yellowstone Lake, declined significantly in the 1960s due to overharvest of mature cutthroat trout by anglers, as well as overharvesting of eggs by hatcheries in the early 20th century. Managers implemented [[catch and release]], which required anglers to return their catches to the lake, and they terminated hatchery operations in the park which allowed the cutthroat trout to recover.<ref name=ynpfishes>{{cite book|last1=Schullery|first1=Paul|authorlink=Paul Schullery|author2=Varley, John D.|title=Yellowstone Fishes<U+2014>Ecology, History, and Angling in the Park|publisher=Stackpole Books|location=Mechanicsburg, PA|year=1998|isbn=0-8117-2777-7|chapter=Wilderness Defined-The Evolution of an Ideal|pages=90<U+2013>101}}</ref> Then, in 1994, park officials discovered lake trout {{nowrap|(''Salvelinus namaycush'')}} in Yellowstone Lake. Although lake trout were established in [[Shoshone Lake|Shoshone]], [[Lewis Lake (Wyoming)|Lewis]] and [[Heart Lake (Wyoming)|Heart]] lakes in the Snake River drainage from U.S. government stocking operations in 1890, they were never officially introduced into the Yellowstone River drainage and their presence there is probably the result of accidental or illegal introductions.<ref name=laketrout>{{cite web|editors=Varley, John D.; [[Paul Schullery|Schullery, Paul]]|title=The Yellowstone Lake Crisis: Confronting a Lake Trout Invasion |publisher=National Park Service |url=http://www.nps.gov/yell/planyourvisit/upload/laketrout2.pdf|format=pdf|year=1995|authors=Kaeding, Lynn R.; Boltz, Glenn D.; Carty, Daniel G.|accessdate=2014-03-01|chapter=Lake Trout Discovered In Yellowstone Lake |pages=5<U+2013>6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Kendall|first=W. C.|title=The Fishes of the Yellowstone National Park|publisher=Department of Commerce, Bureau of Fisheries|location=Washington D.C.|pages=22<U+2013>23|year=1921}}</ref> By 2000, the cutthroat trout population had declined to less than 10&nbsp;percent of its early 20th century abundance. However, aggressive lake trout eradication programs have killed over one million lake trout since 1996, and the hope is that this will lead to a restoration of cutthroat numbers.<ref name=YSLakeTrout/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ypf.org/site/News2?page=NewsArticle&id=6562&news_iv_ctrl=1061|title=Lake Trout Suppression and Yellowstone Cutthroat Trout Recovery: It's About More than Just Fish|accessdate=2013-12-23|publisher=Yellowstone Park Foundation |quote=First 15 Years: 500,000 lake trout caught and eliminated. 2011 and 2012: 525,000 lake trout caught and eliminated 2013: 172,000 in the first six weeks of the season.}}</ref> Cutthroat trout co-exist with lake trout in Heart lake, an isolated back-country lake at the head of the [[Heart River (Wyoming)|Heart River]] that gets little angling pressure.<ref>{{cite book |last=Parks|first=Richard |title=Fishing Yellowstone National Park-An Angler's Complete Guide to more than 100 streams, rivers and lakes|publisher=Globe Pequot Press|location=Guildford, CT|pages=107<U+2013>108|isbn=0-7627-2285-1|year=2003|edition=2nd}}</ref>

==Angling==
{{see also|Artisan fishing|Recreational fishing}}
[[File:Cutthroat east canyon record.jpg|thumb|alt=Photo of man hold a very large trout|This {{convert|31.5|in|cm|adj=on}} cutthroat trout set a new Utah state record. As of March 26, 2011, it was the largest cutthroat trout ever caught and released in Utah.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.utahwildlifephotos.com/Fish-fishing/Lakes-and-reservoirs/3661660_qRCFXx#!i=1294000117&k=dT7f6nt&lb=1&s=O|title=Curtis Robinson shows the huge cutthroat trout|publisher=[http://www.utahwildlifephotos.com/ Utah Wildlife Photos]|accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref>]]
Cutthroat trout are prized as a gamefish, particularly by fly anglers. They are regulated as a gamefish in every state and province they occur in. From the Yellowstone cutthroat trout fishery in Yellowstone National Park,<ref name=ynpfishes/><ref>{{cite book |url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951d01956560u;view=1up;seq=80|title=Yellowstone: a natural and human history|author=Wallace, David Rains|publisher=National Park Service |location=Washington, D.C.|year=2001|page=78 |isbn=0-912627-69-7 |quote=...&nbsp;by the 1980s the lake's cutthroats were providing a world-class sport fishery for people as well as a vital food source for grizzlies&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Jacklin, Bob |author2=LaFontaine, Gary|title=Fly Fishing the Yellowstone in the Park|publisher=Globe Pequot Press|location=Guilford, CT|page=110|isbn=1-59228-076-5|year=2004|quote=The Yellowstone River is known widely for two things: The Spectacular Yellowstone Falls and a few miles of world-class dry-fly fishing for native cutthroat trout.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://books.google.com/?id=_nweqC_fUcwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Yellowstone+Fly-Fishing+Guide#v=onepage&q=World%20class&f=false |title=The Yellowstone Fly-Fishing Guide|author1=Matthews, Craig |author2=Molinero, Clayton|publisher=The Globe Pequot Press|location=Guilford, CT|isbn=1-55821-545-X|page=11|quote=In 1994 Yellowstone Park official introduced a fee permit policy to help pay the increased cost of protecting and enhancing this world-class fishery.|year=1997}}</ref> the unique Lahontan cutthroat trout fishery in Pyramid Lake, Nevada, the small stream fisheries of the westslope cutthroat trout to saltwater angling for sea-run cutthroat trout on the Pacific coast,<ref>{{cite book |last=Johnson|first=Les|title=Fly-Fishing Coastal Cutthroat Trout: Flies, Techniques, Conservation |publisher=Frank Amato Publishers|location=Portland, OR|year=2004|isbn=978-1-57188-334-6}}</ref> cutthroat trout are a popular quarry for trout anglers throughout their ranges. The all-tackle world record is {{convert|41|lbs|kg|abbr=on}} caught in Pyramid Lake in December 1925.<ref name=IGFA>{{cite web|url=http://wrec.igfa.org/WRecordsList.aspx?lc=AllTackle&cn=Trout,%20cutthroat|title=Trout, Cutthroat (''Oncorhynchus clarki'') |publisher=International Game Fish Association|accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref> Their propensity to feed on aquatic and terrestrial insects make them an ideal quarry for the fly angler.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McClane|first1=A. J.|author2=Gardner, Keith|title=McClane's Game Fish of North America|chapter=Cutthroat Trout Salmo clarki|publisher=Times Books|location=New York|year=1984|isbn=0-8129-1134-2|pages=94<U+2013>100}}</ref>

===Sea-run fishing along the Pacific coast===
From Alaska to Northern California, coastal cutthroat trout in sea-run, resident stream and lacustrine forms are sought by anglers. [[Puget Sound]] in Washington is a stronghold of sea-run cutthroat trout fishing with its many tributaries and protected saltwater inlets and beaches. Fly anglers search for sea-run cutthroat trout along beaches, river mouths and estuaries year round. In the lower reaches of larger rivers, anglers in [[drift boat]]s float the rivers searching for trout along the wooded shorelines.<ref>{{cite book |last=Johnson|first=Les |title=Fly-Fishing Coastal Cutthroat Trout: Flies, Techniques, Conservation|publisher=Frank Amato Publishers|location=Portland, OR|year=2004|isbn= 978-1-57188-334-6 |chapter=Coastal Cutthroat Trout in Washington|pages=45<U+2013>55}}</ref> In addition to a cutthroat trout sport fishery managed by the Alaska Department of Fish and Game, the Federal Subsistence Management Program<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doi.gov/subsistence/board/index.cfm |title=Federal Subsistence Board |publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture|accessdate=2014-03-04}}</ref> manages coastal cutthroat trout [[Artisan fishing|subsistence]] fisheries in Southeast Alaska.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fws.gov/columbiariver/cctsym/ppt/ppt6.pdf|title=The Status and Management of Coastal Cutthroat Trout in Alaska|publisher=Alaska Department of Fish and Game|accessdate=2014-03-03|format=pdf}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Yellowstone fishery===
[[File:Fishing Bridge ca 1951 YNP.JPG|thumb|alt=Black and White photo of Fishing bridge ca 1951 in Yellowstone National Park |Fishing Bridge ca. 1951 in Yellowstone National Park<ref>{{cite book |title= Nature and Culture at Fishing Bridge-A History of the Fishing Bridge Development in Yellowstone National Park |author=Schullery, Paul|authorlink=Paul Schullery|publisher= National Park Service, Yellowstone Center for Resources Yellowstone National Park, Wyoming|year=2010 |url=http://www.greateryellowstonescience.org/sites/default/files/Fishing%20Bridge%20History%20low%205-7-10.pdf|page=54|chapter=World War II and Mission 66 at Fishing Bridge|format=pdf}}</ref>]]
{{see also|Angling in Yellowstone National Park}}
[[Yellowstone National Park]] was established in 1872. By the 1890s, the Yellowstone cutthroat trout fishery in the [[Yellowstone River]] and Yellowstone Lake were well known and being promoted in national guidebooks.
<small>{{quotation| Fishing Grounds.<U+2014>In the river at the lake outlet are the fishing grounds, about a mile from the hotel, while at many places between the lake and canyon excellent fishing is had from shore. The best results in the outlet are had from row boats; they can be rented from the steamboat company who have a supply, as well as competent and experienced oarsmen. Not more than two can successfully fish from one boat. When the grounds are reached, have the oarsman occupy the "stern," as from this position he can manipulate the landing net to a better advantage, the anchor is attached to the "bow." During the trout season (July to September), no better fishing can be found. They average about one and one-half pounds each and are of the salmon myhiss [sic] variety<U+2014>a catch of 100, three or four hours before sundown, is not unfrequent.| A. B. Guptill, ''Haynes Guide to Yellowstone Park'' (1896)<ref>{{cite book|title= Nature and Culture at Fishing Bridge-A History of the Fishing Bridge Development in Yellowstone National Park|author=Schullery, Paul|authorlink=Paul Schullery|publisher=National Park Service, Yellowstone Center for Resources Yellowstone National Park, Wyoming|year=2010 |url=http://www.greateryellowstonescience.org/sites/default/files/Fishing%20Bridge%20History%20low%205-7-10.pdf|pages=15<U+2013>16|format=pdf}}</ref>}}</small>
In 1902, anticipating the completion of the east entrance road from Cody, Wyoming, Captain [[Hiram M. Chittenden]] supervised the construction of the first "Fishing Bridge" across the outlet of Yellowstone Lake.<ref>{{cite book|title=Nature and Culture at Fishing Bridge-A History of the Fishing Bridge Development in Yellowstone National Park|author=Schullery, Paul |authorlink=Paul Schullery|publisher= National Park Service, Yellowstone Center for Resources Yellowstone National Park, Wyoming|year=2010 |url=http://www.greateryellowstonescience.org/sites/default/files/Fishing%20Bridge%20History%20low%205-7-10.pdf|chapter=The Cody Road and First Bridge|pages=17<U+2013>23|format=pdf}}</ref> Fishing Bridge was rebuilt in 1919, and reconstructed in
1937, primarily to accommodate vehicle traffic. Between 1916 and 1931, a large development of campgrounds, cabins, stores and service facilities were built just east of the bridge to support anglers. This area is now known as the Fishing Bridge Historic District.<ref>{{cite book |title= Nature and Culture at Fishing Bridge-A History of the Fishing Bridge Development in Yellowstone National Park |author=Schullery, Paul|authorlink=Paul Schullery|publisher= National Park Service, Yellowstone Center for Resources Yellowstone National Park, Wyoming|year=2010 |url=http://www.greateryellowstonescience.org/sites/default/files/Fishing%20Bridge%20History%20low%205-7-10.pdf|pages=25<U+2013>50|chapter=The Development of the Fishing Bridge Area, 1918<U+2013>1941|format=pdf}}</ref> The 1937 bridge boasted pedestrian walkways on either side of the roadway to give more room to anglers. Angling in the river, at Fishing Bridge and in the lake, boomed during the 1950s and 1960s and over harvest caused a significant decline in the fishery. Consequently, in 1973, fishing was no longer permitted from Fishing Bridge.<ref name=Grand1950s>{{Cite journal|last=Franke |first=Mary Ann |authorlink= |date=Winter 1997 |title=A Grand Experiment<U+2014>The Tide Turns in the 1950s: Part II |journal=Yellowstone Science |volume=5 |issue=1 |page=9 |url=http://www.nps.gov/yell/planyourvisit/upload/vol5-1.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2014-04-09}}</ref>

===Pyramid Lake Lahontan subspecies fishery===
[[File:Pyramid Lake Lahontan Cutthroat Fishery.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Photo of angler on ladder in lake|Angler fishing for Lahontan cutthroat trout in Pyramid Lake, Nevada]]
The Pyramid Lake strain of Lahontan cutthroat trout, source of the {{convert|41|lbs|adj=on}} world record and native to Pyramid Lake, Lake Tahoe and the Truckee River, was brought to near-extinction in the two decades between the 1920s-40s from overharvest, introduced species and loss of spawning habitat. In the 1970s, Pyramid Lake was stocked with Lahontan cutthroat trout strains still surviving in some nearby lakes, but they were not the large Pyramid Lake strain. Although the [[Paiute people|Paiute tribe]] had been successful in reestablishing a cutthroat trout fishery on the reservation in Pyramid Lake, the cutthroat trout were not the large fish of the late 19th and early 20th century. In the late 1970, biologists discovered a surviving population of a pure Pyramid Lake strain in a small headwaters stream on the Nevada-Utah border that had at some point around 1900 been introduced into the stream. In 1995, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service began rearing these fish in the Lahontan National Fish Hatchery<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fws.gov/lahontannfhc/lnfh.html|title=Lahontan National Fish Hatchery |publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service|accessdate=2014-03-04}}</ref> in [[Gardnerville, Nevada]]. In 2006, the Pyramid Lake strain of Lahontan cutthroat trout were reintroduced into the lake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/24/us/lahontan-cutthroat-trout-make-a-comeback.html?_r=0|title=20 Pounds? Not Too Bad, for an Extinct Fish |publisher=New York Times |author=Schweber, Nate|date=April 23, 2013|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref> As Pyramid Lake has a very shallow shoreline, anglers use ladders to stand comfortably in {{convert|3|to|4|ft|m|1}} of water and cast to trout cruising along shoreline breaks. Considered a "world-class" fishery, anglers routinely catch cutthroat trout exceeding {{convert|10|lbs|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pyramidlakefisheries.org/|title=Pyramid Lake Fisheries|publisher=Pyramid Lake Fisheries.org|accessdate=2014-03-03 |quote=Pyramid Lake is widely regarded as a world class fishery for the Lahontan Cutthroat Trout.}}</ref>

==As a symbol==
The cutthroat trout is the [[state fish]] of Idaho, Montana and Wyoming, while particular subspecies of cutthroat are the state fish of Colorado, Nevada, New Mexico and Utah.
* Idaho<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.idaho.gov/elect/emblem.htm |title=Idaho State Emblems |publisher=Idaho Secretary of State|accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref> Montana<ref>{{cite web |url=http://leg.mt.gov/bills/mca/1/1/1-1-507.htm|title=Montana Code Annotated 2013 State Fish |publisher=mt.gov |accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref> and Wyoming<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soswy.state.wy.us/Information/StateInfo_Symbols.aspx |title=State Symbols |publisher=Wyoming Secretary of State|accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref><U+2013>Cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. clarki'')}}
* Colorado<U+2013>Greenback cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. stomias'')}}
* Nevada<ref>{{cite web |url=http://leg.state.nv.us/general/nvfacts/index.cfm|title=Nevada Facts and State Symbols |publisher= |accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref><U+2013>Lahontan cutthroat trout {{nowrap|''O. c. henshawi''}}
* New Mexico<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos.state.nm.us/Kids_Corner/State_Symbols.aspx#fish |title=State Symbols|publisher=New Mexico Secretary of State|accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref><U+2013>Rio Grande cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. virginalis'')}}
* Utah<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pioneer.utah.gov/research/utah_symbols/fish.html |title=Utah State Fish&nbsp;<U+2014> Bonneville Cutthroat Trout |publisher=Pioneer Utah's Online Library|accessdate=2013-12-23}}</ref><U+2013>Bonneville cutthroat trout {{nowrap|(''O. c. utah'')}}

